data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>`, which gives a clear failure message instead of an `InvalidCastException` on wrong types:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

The generic overload (MSTest v3+) both asserts the type **and** returns the cast object, so you can keep testing properties without a separate cast. For older MSTest, use the non-generic form:

```csharp
Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler));
var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
```
